import{_ as a,o as e,c as n,a2 as o}from"./chunks/framework.B72_uj9U.js";const y=JSON.parse('{"title":"Project Structure","description":"Organize a Rust binary project with a clear directory layout that scales as your coding agent grows across chapters.","frontmatter":{"title":"Project Structure","description":"Organize a Rust binary project with a clear directory layout that scales as your coding agent grows across chapters."},"headers":[],"relativePath":"learn/project/01-hello-rust-cli/05-project-structure.md","filePath":"learn/project/01-hello-rust-cli/05-project-structure.md"}'),t={name:"learn/project/01-hello-rust-cli/05-project-structure.md"};function r(l,s,c,p,i,d){return e(),n("div",null,[...s[0]||(s[0]=[o(`<h1 id="project-structure" tabindex="-1">Project Structure <a class="header-anchor" href="#project-structure" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;Project Structure&quot;">​</a></h1><blockquote><p><strong>What you&#39;ll learn:</strong></p><ul><li>How to lay out <code>src/main.rs</code>, <code>src/lib.rs</code>, and supporting modules for a CLI application</li><li>The role of <code>Cargo.toml</code>, <code>Cargo.lock</code>, and the <code>target/</code> directory in a Rust project</li><li>How to structure your coding-agent project so it scales as you add features in later chapters</li></ul></blockquote><p>A well-organized project structure saves you hours of confusion later. When your coding agent grows to include an LLM client, tool execution, context management, and a terminal UI, you need to know exactly where each piece lives. Rust has strong conventions for project layout, and Cargo enforces many of them automatically.</p><p>Let&#39;s look at what you have now and plan where it is going.</p><h2 id="the-default-layout" tabindex="-1">The Default Layout <a class="header-anchor" href="#the-default-layout" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;The Default Layout&quot;">​</a></h2><p>After running <code>cargo new kodai</code>, you have this structure:</p><div class="language-"><button title="Copy Code" class="copy"></button><span class="lang"></span><pre class="shiki catppuccin-mocha vp-code" tabindex="0"><code><span class="line"><span>kodai/</span></span>
<span class="line"><span>  Cargo.toml          # Project manifest (name, version, dependencies)</span></span>
<span class="line"><span>  Cargo.lock          # Exact dependency versions (generated by Cargo)</span></span>
<span class="line"><span>  .gitignore          # Ignores target/ directory</span></span>
<span class="line"><span>  src/</span></span>
<span class="line"><span>    main.rs           # Binary entry point</span></span>
<span class="line"><span>  target/             # Compiled artifacts (generated, never commit)</span></span>
<span class="line"><span>    debug/</span></span>
<span class="line"><span>      kodai           # Your compiled binary</span></span></code></pre></div><p>This is the minimal layout for a binary project. Let&#39;s understand each piece.</p><h3 id="cargo-toml-—-the-single-source-of-truth" tabindex="-1">Cargo.toml — The Single Source of Truth <a class="header-anchor" href="#cargo-toml-—-the-single-source-of-truth" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;Cargo.toml — The Single Source of Truth&quot;">​</a></h3><p><code>Cargo.toml</code> is the project manifest. It tells Cargo your project&#39;s name, version, Rust edition, and dependencies. As the project grows, you also add build metadata, feature flags, and compiler settings here.</p><div class="language-toml"><button title="Copy Code" class="copy"></button><span class="lang">toml</span><pre class="shiki catppuccin-mocha vp-code" tabindex="0"><code><span class="line"><span style="color:#9399B2;">[</span><span style="color:#CDD6F4;">package</span><span style="color:#9399B2;">]</span></span>
<span class="line"><span style="color:#CDD6F4;">name </span><span style="color:#94E2D5;">=</span><span style="color:#A6E3A1;"> &quot;kodai&quot;</span></span>
<span class="line"><span style="color:#CDD6F4;">version </span><span style="color:#94E2D5;">=</span><span style="color:#A6E3A1;"> &quot;0.1.0&quot;</span></span>
<span class="line"><span style="color:#CDD6F4;">edition </span><span style="color:#94E2D5;">=</span><span style="color:#A6E3A1;"> &quot;2021&quot;</span></span>
<span class="line"></span>
<span class="line"><span style="color:#9399B2;">[</span><span style="color:#CDD6F4;">dependencies</span><span style="color:#9399B2;">]</span></span></code></pre></div><p>Every Rust project has exactly one <code>Cargo.toml</code> at the root. It is the equivalent of combining Python&#39;s <code>pyproject.toml</code>, <code>setup.py</code>, and <code>requirements.txt</code> into a single file.</p><h3 id="cargo-lock-—-reproducible-builds" tabindex="-1">Cargo.lock — Reproducible Builds <a class="header-anchor" href="#cargo-lock-—-reproducible-builds" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;Cargo.lock — Reproducible Builds&quot;">​</a></h3><p>When Cargo resolves dependencies, it records the exact versions in <code>Cargo.lock</code>. This file ensures that everyone who builds your project gets identical dependency versions.</p><p><strong>For binary projects (applications), commit <code>Cargo.lock</code> to Git.</strong> This guarantees reproducible builds. For library crates, the convention is to not commit it — but since we are building a CLI application, always commit it.</p><h3 id="src-main-rs-—-the-binary-entry-point" tabindex="-1">src/main.rs — The Binary Entry Point <a class="header-anchor" href="#src-main-rs-—-the-binary-entry-point" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;src/main.rs — The Binary Entry Point&quot;">​</a></h3><p>Cargo looks for <code>src/main.rs</code> to build a binary. The <code>main</code> function inside it is the program&#39;s entry point. You do not configure this anywhere — Cargo uses this convention automatically.</p><h3 id="target-—-build-artifacts" tabindex="-1">target/ — Build Artifacts <a class="header-anchor" href="#target-—-build-artifacts" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;target/ — Build Artifacts&quot;">​</a></h3><p>Everything Cargo compiles goes into <code>target/</code>. This directory is in <code>.gitignore</code> by default and can grow to hundreds of megabytes. You never need to look inside it except to find your compiled binary at <code>target/debug/kodai</code> (or <code>target/release/kodai</code> for release builds).</p><div class="custom-block python"><p class="custom-block-title">Coming from Python</p><p>A Python project might scatter configuration across <code>pyproject.toml</code>, <code>setup.cfg</code>, <code>requirements.txt</code>, <code>MANIFEST.in</code>, and <code>setup.py</code>. A Rust project puts everything in <code>Cargo.toml</code>. The <code>target/</code> directory is like <code>__pycache__</code>, <code>.eggs</code>, and <code>dist/</code> combined — all build artifacts in one place that you never commit.</p></div><h2 id="adding-src-lib-rs-—-the-library-root" tabindex="-1">Adding src/lib.rs — The Library Root <a class="header-anchor" href="#adding-src-lib-rs-—-the-library-root" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;Adding src/lib.rs — The Library Root&quot;">​</a></h2><p>As your project grows, you do not want everything in <code>main.rs</code>. Rust projects conventionally split into two parts:</p><ul><li><strong><code>src/main.rs</code></strong> — the binary entry point. It handles startup, CLI parsing, and calls into the library.</li><li><strong><code>src/lib.rs</code></strong> — the library root. It contains your actual application logic, organized into modules.</li></ul><p>Create <code>src/lib.rs</code>:</p><div class="language-rust"><button title="Copy Code" class="copy"></button><span class="lang">rust</span><pre class="shiki catppuccin-mocha vp-code" tabindex="0"><code><span class="line"><span style="color:#CBA6F7;">pub</span><span style="color:#CBA6F7;"> fn</span><span style="color:#89B4FA;font-style:italic;"> greet</span><span style="color:#9399B2;">(</span><span style="color:#EBA0AC;">name</span><span style="color:#94E2D5;">:</span><span style="color:#94E2D5;"> &amp;</span><span style="color:#F9E2AF;font-style:italic;">str</span><span style="color:#9399B2;">)</span><span style="color:#94E2D5;"> -&gt;</span><span style="color:#F9E2AF;font-style:italic;"> String</span><span style="color:#9399B2;"> {</span></span>
<span class="line"><span style="color:#89B4FA;font-style:italic;">    format!</span><span style="color:#9399B2;">(</span><span style="color:#A6E3A1;">&quot;Hello, </span><span style="color:#9399B2;">{</span><span style="color:#A6E3A1;">name</span><span style="color:#9399B2;">}</span><span style="color:#A6E3A1;">! Welcome to Kodai.&quot;</span><span style="color:#9399B2;">)</span></span>
<span class="line"><span style="color:#9399B2;">}</span></span></code></pre></div><p>Now update <code>src/main.rs</code> to use it:</p><div class="language-rust"><button title="Copy Code" class="copy"></button><span class="lang">rust</span><pre class="shiki catppuccin-mocha vp-code" tabindex="0"><code><span class="line"><span style="color:#CBA6F7;">use</span><span style="color:#F9E2AF;"> kodai</span><span style="color:#94E2D5;">::</span><span style="color:#CDD6F4;">greet</span><span style="color:#9399B2;">;</span></span>
<span class="line"></span>
<span class="line"><span style="color:#CBA6F7;">fn</span><span style="color:#89B4FA;font-style:italic;"> main</span><span style="color:#9399B2;">()</span><span style="color:#9399B2;"> {</span></span>
<span class="line"><span style="color:#CBA6F7;">    let</span><span style="color:#CDD6F4;"> message </span><span style="color:#94E2D5;">=</span><span style="color:#89B4FA;font-style:italic;"> greet</span><span style="color:#9399B2;">(</span><span style="color:#A6E3A1;">&quot;developer&quot;</span><span style="color:#9399B2;">);</span></span>
<span class="line"><span style="color:#89B4FA;font-style:italic;">    println!</span><span style="color:#9399B2;">(</span><span style="color:#A6E3A1;">&quot;</span><span style="color:#9399B2;">{</span><span style="color:#A6E3A1;">message</span><span style="color:#9399B2;">}</span><span style="color:#A6E3A1;">&quot;</span><span style="color:#9399B2;">);</span></span>
<span class="line"><span style="color:#9399B2;">}</span></span></code></pre></div><p>Run <code>cargo run</code> and you see:</p><div class="language-"><button title="Copy Code" class="copy"></button><span class="lang"></span><pre class="shiki catppuccin-mocha vp-code" tabindex="0"><code><span class="line"><span>Hello, developer! Welcome to Kodai.</span></span></code></pre></div><p>The <code>use kodai::greet</code> line imports the <code>greet</code> function from your library crate. The library&#39;s crate name matches the <code>name</code> field in <code>Cargo.toml</code> (which is <code>kodai</code>). The <code>pub</code> keyword on <code>greet</code> makes it public — visible outside the module. Without <code>pub</code>, the function would be private and <code>main.rs</code> could not access it.</p><p>This split has a practical benefit: code in <code>src/lib.rs</code> can be tested independently, imported by integration tests, and eventually reused if you want to expose your agent as a library.</p><h2 id="planning-for-growth" tabindex="-1">Planning for Growth <a class="header-anchor" href="#planning-for-growth" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;Planning for Growth&quot;">​</a></h2><p>By the end of this book, your coding agent has many components. Here is the structure you are working toward:</p><div class="language-"><button title="Copy Code" class="copy"></button><span class="lang"></span><pre class="shiki catppuccin-mocha vp-code" tabindex="0"><code><span class="line"><span>kodai/</span></span>
<span class="line"><span>  Cargo.toml</span></span>
<span class="line"><span>  Cargo.lock</span></span>
<span class="line"><span>  src/</span></span>
<span class="line"><span>    main.rs              # Entry point: CLI parsing, startup</span></span>
<span class="line"><span>    lib.rs               # Library root: re-exports modules</span></span>
<span class="line"><span>    repl.rs              # The REPL loop</span></span>
<span class="line"><span>    agent/</span></span>
<span class="line"><span>      mod.rs             # Agent module root</span></span>
<span class="line"><span>      loop.rs            # The agentic loop</span></span>
<span class="line"><span>      context.rs         # Context/message management</span></span>
<span class="line"><span>    llm/</span></span>
<span class="line"><span>      mod.rs             # LLM client module root</span></span>
<span class="line"><span>      client.rs          # HTTP client for API calls</span></span>
<span class="line"><span>      streaming.rs       # Server-sent events parsing</span></span>
<span class="line"><span>    tools/</span></span>
<span class="line"><span>      mod.rs             # Tool registry and dispatch</span></span>
<span class="line"><span>      shell.rs           # Shell command execution</span></span>
<span class="line"><span>      file_read.rs       # File reading tool</span></span>
<span class="line"><span>      file_write.rs      # File writing tool</span></span>
<span class="line"><span>  tests/</span></span>
<span class="line"><span>    integration_test.rs  # Integration tests</span></span></code></pre></div><p>You do not need to create all of these now. The point is to see where the project is headed. Each directory under <code>src/</code> is a <em>module</em> — Rust&#39;s way of organizing code into namespaces. You learn how to create modules in the next subchapter.</p><p>For now, your project looks like this:</p><div class="language-"><button title="Copy Code" class="copy"></button><span class="lang"></span><pre class="shiki catppuccin-mocha vp-code" tabindex="0"><code><span class="line"><span>kodai/</span></span>
<span class="line"><span>  Cargo.toml</span></span>
<span class="line"><span>  Cargo.lock</span></span>
<span class="line"><span>  src/</span></span>
<span class="line"><span>    main.rs</span></span>
<span class="line"><span>    lib.rs</span></span></code></pre></div><p>This is the foundation everything builds on.</p><h2 id="binary-vs-library-crates" tabindex="-1">Binary vs. Library Crates <a class="header-anchor" href="#binary-vs-library-crates" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;Binary vs. Library Crates&quot;">​</a></h2><p>Rust distinguishes between two kinds of crates:</p><table tabindex="0"><thead><tr><th></th><th>Binary Crate</th><th>Library Crate</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Entry file</td><td><code>src/main.rs</code></td><td><code>src/lib.rs</code></td></tr><tr><td>Output</td><td>An executable binary</td><td>Code other crates can import</td></tr><tr><td>Has <code>main()</code>?</td><td>Yes, required</td><td>No</td></tr><tr><td>Can have both?</td><td>Yes — one project can have both</td><td></td></tr></tbody></table><p>Your project has both: <code>src/main.rs</code> makes it a binary crate (you can run it), and <code>src/lib.rs</code> makes it also a library crate (its code can be imported). This is the standard pattern for CLI applications in Rust.</p><div class="custom-block python"><p class="custom-block-title">Coming from Python</p><p>In Python, the distinction between a script and a library is informal — any <code>.py</code> file can be both. In Rust, <code>main.rs</code> and <code>lib.rs</code> formally define the binary and library sides of your project. The binary is a thin entry point that calls into the library, keeping your logic testable and reusable. Think of <code>main.rs</code> as your <code>__main__.py</code> and <code>lib.rs</code> as your package&#39;s <code>__init__.py</code>.</p></div><h2 id="the-tests-directory" tabindex="-1">The tests/ Directory <a class="header-anchor" href="#the-tests-directory" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;The tests/ Directory&quot;">​</a></h2><p>Rust has two kinds of tests:</p><ol><li><strong>Unit tests</strong> — live inside source files, in <code>#[cfg(test)]</code> modules (you saw these in the Cargo Basics subchapter).</li><li><strong>Integration tests</strong> — live in the <code>tests/</code> directory at the project root.</li></ol><p>Integration tests import your library crate from the outside, just like an external user would:</p><div class="language-rust"><button title="Copy Code" class="copy"></button><span class="lang">rust</span><pre class="shiki catppuccin-mocha vp-code" tabindex="0"><code><span class="line"><span style="color:#6C7086;font-style:italic;">// tests/integration_test.rs</span></span>
<span class="line"><span style="color:#CBA6F7;">use</span><span style="color:#F9E2AF;"> kodai</span><span style="color:#94E2D5;">::</span><span style="color:#CDD6F4;">greet</span><span style="color:#9399B2;">;</span></span>
<span class="line"></span>
<span class="line"><span style="color:#F9E2AF;font-style:italic;">#</span><span style="color:#9399B2;">[</span><span style="color:#F9E2AF;font-style:italic;">test</span><span style="color:#9399B2;">]</span></span>
<span class="line"><span style="color:#CBA6F7;">fn</span><span style="color:#89B4FA;font-style:italic;"> test_greet_returns_welcome_message</span><span style="color:#9399B2;">()</span><span style="color:#9399B2;"> {</span></span>
<span class="line"><span style="color:#CBA6F7;">    let</span><span style="color:#CDD6F4;"> result </span><span style="color:#94E2D5;">=</span><span style="color:#89B4FA;font-style:italic;"> greet</span><span style="color:#9399B2;">(</span><span style="color:#A6E3A1;">&quot;Alice&quot;</span><span style="color:#9399B2;">);</span></span>
<span class="line"><span style="color:#89B4FA;font-style:italic;">    assert!</span><span style="color:#9399B2;">(</span><span style="color:#CDD6F4;">result</span><span style="color:#94E2D5;">.</span><span style="color:#89B4FA;font-style:italic;">contains</span><span style="color:#9399B2;">(</span><span style="color:#A6E3A1;">&quot;Alice&quot;</span><span style="color:#9399B2;">));</span></span>
<span class="line"><span style="color:#89B4FA;font-style:italic;">    assert!</span><span style="color:#9399B2;">(</span><span style="color:#CDD6F4;">result</span><span style="color:#94E2D5;">.</span><span style="color:#89B4FA;font-style:italic;">contains</span><span style="color:#9399B2;">(</span><span style="color:#A6E3A1;">&quot;Kodai&quot;</span><span style="color:#9399B2;">));</span></span>
<span class="line"><span style="color:#9399B2;">}</span></span></code></pre></div><p>Create the <code>tests/</code> directory and this file, then run:</p><div class="language-bash"><button title="Copy Code" class="copy"></button><span class="lang">bash</span><pre class="shiki catppuccin-mocha vp-code" tabindex="0"><code><span class="line"><span style="color:#89B4FA;font-style:italic;">cargo</span><span style="color:#A6E3A1;"> test</span></span></code></pre></div><p>Cargo finds and runs both unit tests (in <code>src/</code>) and integration tests (in <code>tests/</code>) automatically. No test discovery configuration needed.</p><h2 id="workspaces-a-preview" tabindex="-1">Workspaces (A Preview) <a class="header-anchor" href="#workspaces-a-preview" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;Workspaces (A Preview)&quot;">​</a></h2><p>As projects grow very large, Rust supports <em>workspaces</em> — multiple crates in a single repository that share dependencies and compile together. You will not need workspaces for this book, but it is worth knowing they exist. A workspace looks like:</p><div class="language-"><button title="Copy Code" class="copy"></button><span class="lang"></span><pre class="shiki catppuccin-mocha vp-code" tabindex="0"><code><span class="line"><span>my-workspace/</span></span>
<span class="line"><span>  Cargo.toml          # Workspace root</span></span>
<span class="line"><span>  kodai-cli/           # Binary crate</span></span>
<span class="line"><span>    Cargo.toml</span></span>
<span class="line"><span>    src/main.rs</span></span>
<span class="line"><span>  kodai-core/          # Library crate</span></span>
<span class="line"><span>    Cargo.toml</span></span>
<span class="line"><span>    src/lib.rs</span></span></code></pre></div><p>Production coding agents often use this pattern to separate the CLI frontend from the core logic. For now, a single crate with <code>main.rs</code> and <code>lib.rs</code> gives you everything you need.</p><h2 id="key-takeaways" tabindex="-1">Key Takeaways <a class="header-anchor" href="#key-takeaways" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;Key Takeaways&quot;">​</a></h2><ul><li>Rust projects have a conventional layout: <code>Cargo.toml</code> at the root, source code in <code>src/</code>, build artifacts in <code>target/</code>, and integration tests in <code>tests/</code>.</li><li>Split your project into <code>src/main.rs</code> (thin binary entry point) and <code>src/lib.rs</code> (application logic) early — this keeps code testable and organized.</li><li><code>Cargo.lock</code> pins exact dependency versions. Commit it for binary projects to guarantee reproducible builds.</li><li>The <code>target/</code> directory contains all compiled artifacts. Never commit it, and use <code>cargo clean</code> to reclaim disk space when needed.</li><li>Plan your module structure early. The directory layout you choose now scales to the full coding agent you build throughout this book.</li></ul>`,57)])])}const h=a(t,[["render",r]]);export{y as __pageData,h as default};
